    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This paper proposes using nuclear fusion reactors as a novel source of exotic lightweight particles: the intense neutron bombardment of lithium in reactor walls could generate feebly-interacting \"dark sector\" scalars that a nearby detector might catch. The review board found the core idea creative and physically plausible, and the paper is published in a reputable peer-reviewed journal. The main caveat is that quantitative sensitivity projections rest partly on rough estimates rather than full nuclear calculations, and the review board's limited access to the full text prevented verification of the central sensitivity figures and claims of \"leading constraints.\"",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The paper proposes DT fusion reactor tritium breeding blankets as production environments for feebly-coupled light scalars and pseudoscalars via neutron capture on Li-6/Li-7, estimating leading-edge constraints on scalar- and pseudoscalar-nucleon couplings from year-long searches at ITER, DEMO, and ARC. Multiple unresolved technical concerns were identified: a potential dimensional inconsistency in the neutron flux normalization (Eq. 3.10, where P/14.1 MeV is a neutron rate, not a flux density); an unverified sign in the detector event-rate distance scaling (Eqs. 4.6\u20134.7, reportedly scaling as (L/10 m)\u00b2 rather than 1/L\u00b2); NDA-level scalar production estimates without dedicated nuclear matrix element calculations (Eqs. 3.8\u20133.9); and an underdeveloped near-reactor background model. The \"leading constraints\" claim cannot be assessed without inspecting the exclusion plots overlaid against stellar cooling and SN1987A bounds."
